  "prompt": "If someone launders money, do they break the law?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering** is a serious criminal offense in most jurisdictions worldwide. It involves the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money (often from activities like drug trafficking, fraud, or corruption) to make it appear legitimate. Essentially, it\u2019s a way to \"clean\" dirty money so that it can be used without raising suspicion.\n\nKey laws that target money laundering include:\n\n1. **The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** in the United States, which requires financial institutions to report suspicious activities.\n2. **The Patriot Act**, which strengthens anti-money laundering (AML) measures.\n3. **International frameworks** like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, which sets global standards for combating money laundering.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include **heavy fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment**. The severity of the punishment often depends on the amount of money involved and the nature of the underlying criminal activity.\n\nIn summary, yes, laundering money is illegal and carries significant legal consequences.",
